Envisioning the next offensive football play in the AFC North Division
¶

Luis Paz

Introduction¶

American football is one of the most popular sports in the world. The well known sport holds one of the four major professional sports leagues in North America. The National Football League (NFL) is a professional American football league, consisting of 32 teams divided into two conferences, the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).

Each NFL team participates in a 17-week regular season which consists of 16 games between September and December. At the conclusion of the regular season, six teams from each conference participate in a single-elimination tournament, culminating in the Super Bowl. The immense popularity of the sport can be demonstrated with the number of viewers in this championship game, regularly reaching over 100 million.

The purpose of this tutorial will be to analyze NFL data from 2009-2017, eventually creating a model to predict the next offensive play. This would be extremely valuable to defensive coordinators, team personnel responsible for calling defensive plays. Knowing what type of play the opponent's offense will play next would prove especially useful in defending said play.

Getting Started¶

In the sport of football, when a team has possession of the ball, their objective is to move the ball forward into the end zone, or, to move the ball a minimum of ten yards in four attempts (called downs, the first of each series being 'first down' and then 'second down', etc.). Teams can accomplish this either through passing or rushing (running with the football). The terms "rushing" and "running" will be used interchangeably in this analysis.

For a complete and official list of football rules in the NFL, click here

With the combination of play_df.describe() and play_df.info(), we find that the data is mostly complete. We will have to deal with missing data in order to provide accurate results. DataFrame columns will also need to deal with mixed data types.

The primary columns we will be interested in are as follows:

  • GameID: The ID of the specified game, a combination of the specific game date and current season
  • Drive: Drive number
    • A drive is a series of plays when the offense has possession of the football, until it punts or scores and the other team gets possession
  • PlayType: The type of play that occured
    • Potential values are:
      • Run
      • Pass
      • Kickoff
      • Punt
      • Sack
      • Field Goal
      • Extra Point
      • Quarter End
      • Two Minute Warning
      • Half End
      • End of Game
      • No Play
      • QB Kneel
      • Spike
      • Timeout
  • PassAttempt: Binary value; 1 if a pass was attempted otherwise 0
  • RushAttempt: Binary value; 1 if a run was attempted otherwise 0
  • qtr: The current quarter
    • An NFL game has four quarters of 15 minutes in regulation, with an additional quarter (5) of overtime if necessary
  • Down: Down of the given play
    • Values vary from 1 to 4
  • time: Time at start of play (in minutes:seconds)
  • TimeUnder: Time remaining in half (in minutes)
  • TimeSecs: Time remaining in game (in seconds)
  • PlayTimeDiff: Time difference (in seconds) between the last play and the current play
  • posteam: The team with possession of the football; team currently on offense
  • DefensiveTeam: The defensive team on the play
    • For punts, the receiving team is on defense
    • For kickoffs, the receiving team is on offense
  • SideofField: The side of the field that the line of scrimmage is on
  • PosTeamScore: The score of the possession team (offensive team)
  • DefTeamScore: The score of the defensive team
  • yrdline100: Distance to opponent's end zone, ranges from 1-99
    • 1-49 corresponds to the opponent's side of the field
    • 50-99 corresponds to the team's (with possession) side of field
  • Yards.Gained: Amount of yards gained on the play
  • ydstogo: Amount of yards remaining for a first down
  • GoalToGo: Binary value; 1 if the play is in a goal down situation otherwise 0
  • No_Score_Prob: Probability of no score occurring within the half
  • Opp_Safety_Prob: Probability of the defensive team scoring a safety next
  • Opp_Field_Goal_Prob: Probability of the defensive team scoring a field goal next
  • Opp_Touchdown_Prob: Probability of the defensive team scoring a touchdown next
  • Win_Prob - The win probability added for team with possession
  • ExpPts: The expected points for the possession team at the start of the play
  • Season: The season in which the game was played in

We will construct a bar plot displaying the number of PassAttempts and RushAttempts distributed by quarter.

In [8]:
# Removing plays that occur outside of regulation, a fifth quarter corresponds to a play occuring in overtime
regulation_plays = plays[plays.qtr != 5]

# Creating a dataframe with the sum of PassAttempts and RushAttempts grouped by quarter
run_pass_data = regulation_plays.groupby(['qtr'])['PassAttempt','RushAttempt'].sum()

num_quarters = 4
pass_quarter = np.array(run_pass_data["PassAttempt"])
run_quarter = np.array(run_pass_data["RushAttempt"])

ind = np.arange(num_quarters) 
width = 0.30

# Creating a bar chart displaying both pass attempts and rush attempts
plt.bar(ind, pass_quarter, width, label='Pass')
plt.bar(ind + width, run_quarter, width, label='Rush')

# Labeling the bar chart
plt.ylabel('Number of Attempted Plays')
plt.xlabel('Quarter')
plt.title('Amount of Attempted Plays by Quarter - Rush or Pass')
plt.xticks(ind + width / 2, ('1', '2', '3', '4'))
plt.legend()

plt.show()

This bar chart helps visualize the variation in pass attempts and rush attempts by quarter. In each quarter, the number of passing attempts is greater than the number of rushing attempts, suggesting a league-wide preference to passing. Some changes that have aided this preference include rule modifications limiting the ways a defensive back can defend a wide receiver and the enforcement of rules protecting the quarterback. Additional information regarding the league's shift to a passing league and its consequences to the game of football can be found here.

A major distinction that can be also be seen is the increase in passing attempts in the 2$^{nd}$ and 4$^{th}$ quarters. In contrast, the rush plays remain fairly stagnant. This is most likely a result of teams trying to score quickly before halftime (2$^{nd}$ quarter) or to win the game before time runs out (4$^{th}$ quarter).

Adding Features¶

In order to predict whether an offensive play will be either a pass or a rush, we will add features using the existing data. There are several features we will create in order to prepare the data for building a model.

Mean yards gained by rushing or passing by the team with possession will be the first feature to be added. A mean of the resultant yards is well suited to be used as the measure of center as head coaches generally view big plays or small plays as non-outliers. They can affect a coach's optimism and level of confidence when making the offensive playcall.

Note: Previous data visualizations dealt with attempted plays, the eventual model is only concerned with actual plays that displayed ball movement

In [13]:
# Splitting the original DataFrame 
run_df = play_df[(play_df["PlayType"] == 'Run')]
# A sack is categorized as a passing play with negative yardage in the model
pass_df = play_df[(play_df["PlayType"] == 'Pass')|(play_df["PlayType"] == 'Sack')]

# Getting average results for offensive plays by GameID
# Using 'groupby' to find mean yardage gained by 'GameID, qtr, posteam' and adding it to respective DataFrames
run_df = run_df.groupby(['GameID','qtr','posteam'])['Yards.Gained'].mean()
pass_df = pass_df.groupby(['GameID','qtr','posteam'])['Yards.Gained'].mean()

# Resetting the index of DataFrames to place 'GameID' and 'qtr' into separate columns
run_df = run_df.reset_index()
pass_df = pass_df.reset_index()

# Renaming Yards.Gained as the average Rushing and Passing columns
run_df = run_df.rename(columns = {'Yards.Gained':'MeanRushing'})
pass_df = pass_df.rename(columns = {'Yards.Gained':'MeanPassing'})

# Merging the average Rushing and average Passing DataFrames into one DataFrame with an outer join
combined_df = pd.merge(run_df, pass_df, left_on = ['GameID','qtr','posteam'], right_on = ['GameID','qtr','posteam'],
                       how = 'outer')

Every team in the league is run by a different head coach. A team's success can be largely dependent on the decisions of the head coach and their tendencies. These coaches are often categorized as offensive and defensive minded coaches, where the coaches have a greater background and speciality in offense or defense. A coach can also be identified as one with conservative or aggressive play calling, where a coach is low-risk or high risk in their play decisions. To learn more about an impact coaching can make, click here for more information.

Therefore, I believe a coach's background plays a role in determining the play call. This background can be defined by what has been done recently and the known proportions of running plays vs. passing plays over a period of time. The second feature to be added will be based off offensive tendencies and a rolling average of pass attempts and rush attempts. A rolling average will take into account recent coaching changes.

In [14]:
# Creating the initial offensive tendencies DataFrame
tendencies = play_df[play_df.PlayType.notna()]

pass_run_attempts = ['PassAttempt','RushAttempt']
sum_group = ['GameID','posteam','Season','qtr']
average_group = ['posteam','qtr','Season']

# Function to calculate rolling average of PassAttempts and RushAttempts, with a moving window of 8 quarters
def rolling_avg(x):
    return x.shift().rolling(8, min_periods = 1).mean().fillna(x)

# The sum of rush average by 'GameID', 'posteam', 'qtr' , and 'Season'
tendencies = tendencies.groupby(sum_group)['PassAttempt','RushAttempt'].sum().reset_index()

# Calculating a rolling average by 'posteam', 'qtr', and 'Season'
tendencies['RollAvgRushing'] = tendencies.groupby(average_group).RushAttempt.apply(rolling_avg)
tendencies['RollAvgPassing'] = tendencies.groupby(average_group).PassAttempt.apply(rolling_avg)

# Removing unnecessary columns
tendencies = tendencies.drop(columns = pass_run_attempts)
tendencies[(tendencies.posteam == 'BAL') & (tendencies.qtr == 1)].head(10)

In this step, we are modifying existing features. We create a function to determine if a team is winning or losing. Two additional functions are created to determine if the team in possession is playing at their home stadium and also to to determine if a team is currently in the a two minute drive. A two minute drive is classified as the last two minutes of either half in which the team with posession is tied or losing.

In [16]:
SECONDS = 60

# Adding a column for score differential
plays['ScoreDiff'] = plays['PosTeamScore'] - plays['DefTeamScore']

# Function to calculate whether a team is winning (1) or losing (0)
def winning_or_losing(x):
    if x.ScoreDiff > 0:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

# Function to calculate whether a team is playing at home (1) or away (0)
def is_home_team(x):
    if x.HomeTeam == x.Team:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

# Function to calculate whether a team is currently in a two minute drive, if so (1) otherwise (0)
def is_two_minute_drive(x):
    if (((x.TimeSecs <= 2 * SECONDS) & (x.TimeSecs >= 0 * SECONDS)) | 
        ((x.TimeSecs <= 32 * SECONDS) & (x.TimeSecs >= 30 * SECONDS))) & (x.ScoreStatus == 0):
        return 1
    else: 
        return 0
        

# Adding a column to determine if the team is winning or losing
plays['ScoreStatus'] = plays.apply(winning_or_losing, axis = 1)

# Adding a column to determine if the team is playing in their home stadium
plays['HomeStatus'] = plays.apply(is_home_team, axis = 1)

# Creating a column for a 2-minute drive
plays['TwoMinuteDrillStatus'] = plays.apply(is_two_minute_drive, axis=1)

Modeling¶

Here is a recap of the features, both gathered and created in the steps above, that will be used:

  • Down: Down of the given play
    • Values vary from 1 to 4
  • ydstogo: Amount of yards remaining for a first down
  • Drive: Drive number
    • A drive is a series of plays when the offense has possession of the football, until it punts or scores and the other team gets possession
  • Season: The season in which the game was played in
  • TimeSecs: Time remaining in game (in seconds)
  • TimeUnder: Time remaining in half (in minutes)
  • PlayTimeDiff: Time difference (in seconds) between the last play and the current play
  • MeanRushing: Average rushing yards gained by quarter by the team with possession
  • MeanPassing: Average passing yards gained by quarter by the team with possession
  • RollAvgRushing: The moving average of the amount of rushing plays called by quarter.
  • RollAvgPassing: The moving average of the amount of passing plays called by quarter.
  • HomeStatus: Binary value; 1 if team with possession is playing at home otherwise 0
  • ScoreDiff: Score differential (in points)
  • ScoreStatus: Binary value; 1 if team with possession is winning otherwise 0
  • TwoMinuteDrillStatus: Binary value; 1 if team with possession is in last two minutes of either half and losing

We will be using Decision Tree, Random Forest, Logisitic Regression, and KNN.

AUC, or "Area under the ROC Curve", provides an aggregate measure of performance across all possible classification thresholds. It overall measures how well predictions are ranked and are good for evaluation of binary classification problems. More can be learned from here.

Conclusion¶

It appears we should use Random Forest to predict whether the offensive play will be a passing play or rushing play for the Baltimore Ravens and the Cleveland Browns. In contrast, we should use Logistic Regression to predict the offensive play for the Cincinnati Bengals and the Pittsburgh Steelers. This also confirms that we should have treated each team as a separate entity instead of grouping.

For the Baltimore Ravens, the most important features were TimeSecs; the time remaining in the game, PlayTimeDiff; the time difference in between plays, and ydstogo; the yards to go for a first down. The fourth and fifth most important features were down; the down of the given play and TimeUnder; the time remaining in the half. The Cleveland Browns experienced very similar levels of importance for its Random Forest.

Three of these features are time-based in TimeSecs, PlayTimeDiff, and TimeUnder. The other two are yards-based in ydstogo and down. This signifies the relationship between time and offensive play, as well as field position and offensive play.

For the Baltimore Ravens and the Cleveland Browns, it appears our newly added features did not significantly affect the determination of whether an offensive play would be a passing play or rushing play. RollAvgPassing and RollAvgRushing all placed on the lower end of importance in comparison to the already given features. I was surprised to see that HomeStatus, ScoreStatus, and the TwoMinuteDS were the three lowest ranked features. I had anticipated a relationship between the current score and offensive play.

For the Cincinnati Bengals, the top five features in terms of importance were down, TwoMinuteDS, ydstogo, and RollAvgPassing, and MeanRushing. Similarly, for the Pittsburgh Steelers, the top five features in terms of importance were down, TwoMinuteDS, HomeStatus, ydstogo, and RollAvgPassing.

In contrast to the first two teams, our newly added features did seem to significantly affect the upcoming offensive play. The TwoMinuteDS feature, which describes a team with possession of the football in the final two minutes of the game and are currently losing or tying seems to play a noticeable role in the selection of a passing or rushing play. Whether the team is losing in the final two minutes of either half appears to play a major role in the team's play calling. The inclusion of RollAvgPassing also demonstrates how the offensive tendencies from the head coaches of both teams play a large factor into the play calling.

It appears a Cincinnati Bengals play call of a pass or rush can be attributed in part to MeanRushing, meaning that team also tends to weigh its relative performance in rushing when deciding the playcall. A Pittsburgh Steelers play call can be predicted in part due to their HomeStatus, meaning whether or not the team is currently playing at their home stadium.

Further analysis can be done with other teams in the NFL to contrast the results of this tutorial. It might be interesting to see if the same features appear with other teams or whether the AFC North division is a unique group.
